## 6. Per-Action Shader Overlay (the "animation on top of the character")

Goal: when a button is pressed, render a short shader effect **over the character** in the Gotchi
scene, on top of the existing sprite animation (`setAction` is NOT replaced — the shader is additive).

### 6.1 Approach (raylib)
- One fragment shader with an `int uMode` uniform selecting the per-action effect. Cheaper and
  simpler than six shaders.
- Draw the existing gotchi sprite normally, then draw a transparent quad covering the character's
  on-screen rect inside `BeginShaderMode/EndShaderMode`. The shader outputs mostly-transparent
  pixels plus the effect (black lines, sparkles, etc.), so the sprite shows through.
- The effect is driven by `uProgress` (0 -> 1 across the action duration) so it eases in/out and
  self-terminates.

### 6.2 STANDING CONSTRAINT: two shader source copies
Per project rule, every shader exists as two C-string copies. Ship both and pick by platform:
- `ACTION_OVERLAY_FS_DESKTOP` — begins `#version 330`
- `ACTION_OVERLAY_FS_WEB` — begins `#version 300 es` (add `precision mediump float;`)
Load with `LoadShaderFromMemory(nullptr, isWeb ? ACTION_OVERLAY_FS_WEB : ACTION_OVERLAY_FS_DESKTOP)`.
No vertex shader override needed (pass `nullptr`); raylib's default vertex path is fine.

### 6.3 Uniforms
| Uniform | Type | Meaning |
|---------|------|---------|
| `uMode` | `int` | 0=Wash(scrub) 1=Groom(sparkle) 2=Feed(chomp) 3=Pet(warm pulse) 4=Play(speed lines) 5=Break(Z/dim) |
| `uProgress` | `float` | 0..1 over the effect duration |
| `uTime` | `float` | seconds, for animating within the effect |
| `uResolution` | `vec2` | quad pixel size (for aspect-correct UVs) |

Cache locations once at init via `GetShaderLocation`; set with `SetShaderValue` each frame the
overlay is active.

### 6.4 Effect intent (keep simple — black lines are fine)
- **Play (4)** — animated black speed lines sweeping across (the "whatever is appropriate" default).
- **Wash (0)** — horizontal scrub lines + faint bubbles.
- **Groom (1)** — a few sparkle points that pop and fade.
- **Feed (2)** — short chomp lines / crumbs falling.
- **Pet (3)** — soft warm radial pulse (low-alpha, no hard geometry).
- **Give a Break (5)** — screen dim + drifting "Z" glyphs (or just a vignette if glyphs are fiddly).

Any effect that can't be done cleanly in the jam window falls back to the Play speed-lines look with
a different tint. The requirement is "something renders on top per action," not six bespoke shaders.

### 6.5 Scene wiring
```cpp
// GotchiScene.hpp
Shader actionShader_{};
int locMode_ = -1, locProgress_ = -1, locTime_ = -1, locResolution_ = -1;
float actionOverlayTimer_ = 0.0f;    // counts down
float actionOverlayDuration_ = 0.0f; // total, for progress
int   actionOverlayMode_ = -1;

// GotchiScene init (after window/context exists)
const char* fs = isWeb ? ACTION_OVERLAY_FS_WEB : ACTION_OVERLAY_FS_DESKTOP;
actionShader_ = LoadShaderFromMemory(nullptr, fs);
locMode_       = GetShaderLocation(actionShader_, "uMode");
locProgress_   = GetShaderLocation(actionShader_, "uProgress");
locTime_       = GetShaderLocation(actionShader_, "uTime");
locResolution_ = GetShaderLocation(actionShader_, "uResolution");

// trigger, called from handleGotchiAction
void GotchiScene::triggerActionShader(int mode, float duration) {
    actionOverlayMode_ = mode;
    actionOverlayDuration_ = duration;
    actionOverlayTimer_ = duration;
}

// update()
if (actionOverlayTimer_ > 0.0f) actionOverlayTimer_ -= deltaTime;

// draw(), AFTER gotchi->draw()
if (actionOverlayTimer_ > 0.0f && actionOverlayMode_ >= 0) {
    Rectangle r = getGotchiScreenRect();  // character bounds in screen space
    float progress = 1.0f - (actionOverlayTimer_ / actionOverlayDuration_);
    float t = (float)GetTime();
    Vector2 res = { r.width, r.height };
    SetShaderValue(actionShader_, locMode_, &actionOverlayMode_, SHADER_UNIFORM_INT);
    SetShaderValue(actionShader_, locProgress_, &progress, SHADER_UNIFORM_FLOAT);
    SetShaderValue(actionShader_, locTime_, &t, SHADER_UNIFORM_FLOAT);
    SetShaderValue(actionShader_, locResolution_, &res, SHADER_UNIFORM_VEC2);
    BeginShaderMode(actionShader_);
        DrawRectangleRec(r, WHITE);  // shader paints; alpha lets sprite show through
    EndShaderMode();
}

// unload on scene teardown
if (actionShader_.id) UnloadShader(actionShader_);
```
`getGotchiScreenRect()` must return the character's current on-screen rectangle (sprite origin +
size, after any camera/scale). If the scene has no such helper yet, add one; do not hardcode.

